https://twitter.com/realdonaldtrump/status/814919370711461890?lang=en
	Great move on delay (by V. Putin) - I always knew he was very smart!
	11:41 AM - 30 Dec 2016 


Obama and Biden promise discrete retaliation for Russian election meddling, but former CIA director Mike Morell disagrees and calls for something overt. Russian propagandists later use this to blame the U.S. for the assassination of a Russian diplomat, and Russian propaganda outlets also hint at foul play in the crash of a Russian military jet that killed 60 members of a famous Russian military choir. It is unclear if the Obama Administration or Flynn understand Morell to be a Russian agent of influence, or if Trump or Flynn think the incidents constituted retaliation by the U.S. Regardless, Flynn is said to have referenced both incidents in his later calls with Kislyak.

Actor Tom Arnold claims on twitter that Russia can blackmail Trump. Arnold mostly talks about embarrassing tapes of Trump but also mentions his taxes. Most media outlets focus on the claims of tapes and generally don't take him seriously. Trump had previously denied there were any improper dealings with Russians were in his tax returns, saying he would release them when they are no longer under audit.

Trump learns that the Obama administration is planning to sanction Russia for the election meddling. When asked if the U.S. should sanction Russia, Trump says "I think we ought to get on with our lives" and casts doubt that Russia is to blame. That same day, Mike Flynn contacts Russian ambassador Kislyak to arrange a phone call between Trump and Putin.

The next day, the Obama administration officially sanctions Russia for "eroding faith in U.S. Institutions" and "sowing doubt about the integrity of our electoral process," sanctioning Russian intelligence officers and expelling 35 Russian diplomats. The FBI and DHS also release a report on how investigators linked the hacking to the Russian government. Putin makes public his warnings of retaliation and hopes the Trump administration will reverse the sanctions. Tom Arnold calls on hackers to find Trump's tax returns.

Flynn holds five calls with the Russian ambassador between the time the Russian embassy was notified of the sanctions and the time Putin decides against retaliation. Reportedly, Flynn urges Kislyak against retaliation and leaves an impression that the sanctions would be revisited by Trump. Trump tells reporters it's time "to move on" from claims of Russian interference, but promises to meet with the intelligence community to "be updated on the facts of this situation." Sean Spicer dismisses the claims of Russian interference as "unsourced media accounts." After Putin decides against retaliation, Trump praises him on twitter, saying "Great move on delay (by V. Putin) - I always knew he was very smart!"


https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/31/us/politics/donald-trump-russia-hacking.html
	Trump Promises a Revelation on Hacking

	By MAGGIE HABERMAN
	DEC. 31, 2016

	President-elect Donald J. Trump, expressing lingering skepticism about intelligence assessments of Russian interference in the election, said on Saturday evening that he knew “things that other people don’t know” about the hacking, and that the information would be revealed “on Tuesday or Wednesday.”

	Speaking to a handful of reporters outside his Palm Beach, Fla., club, Mar-a-Lago, Mr. Trump cast his declarations of doubt as an effort to seek the truth.

	“I just want them to be sure because it’s a pretty serious charge,” Mr. Trump said of the intelligence agencies. “If you look at the weapons of mass destruction, that was a disaster, and they were wrong,” he added, referring to intelligence cited by the George W. Bush administration to support its march to war in 2003. “So I want them to be sure,” the president-elect said. “I think it’s unfair if they don’t know.”

	He added: “And I know a lot about hacking. And hacking is a very hard thing to prove. So it could be somebody else. And I also know things that other people don’t know, and so they cannot be sure of the situation.”

	When asked what he knew that others did not, Mr. Trump demurred, saying only, “You’ll find out on Tuesday or Wednesday.”

	Mr. Trump, who does not use email, also advised people to avoid computers when dealing with delicate material. “It’s very important, if you have something really important, write it out and have it delivered by courier, the old-fashioned way, because I’ll tell you what, no computer is safe,” Mr. Trump said.

	“I don’t care what they say, no computer is safe,” he added. “I have a boy who’s 10 years old; he can do anything with a computer. You want something to really go without detection, write it out and have it sent by courier.”

	The comments on Saturday were a departure from a statement that Mr. Trump issued through transition officials last week, in which he said that it was time for people to “move on” from the hacking issue but that he would be briefed on the matter by intelligence officials early in the new year.

	...Mr. Trump, who has sought a warmer relationship with Mr. Putin, has repeatedly scoffed at the notion that Russia was behind the hacking, a stance at odds with members of his own party. At one point, Mr. Trump declared that the hacking may have been the work of “someone sitting on their bed weighing 400 pounds.”


