The hunt for Donald Trump's tax returns continues. Grassley reveals that Comey is under scrutiny for the alleged FBI involvement with the "dirty dossier." Trump schedules a call with Putin.

Russian spy Julia Ioffe says the call is no big deal and "bleak" for Putin. During the call, Trump and Putin discuss Putin's "new ideas" for deeper cooperation in Syria and schedule a meeting for July. Putin asks Trump to meet Lavrov during his visit next week. Trump relies "yes."

Trump blasts Comey on twitter. At a hearing the next day, Comey struggles to find an excuse for his actions during the 2016 election. Spicer maintains that Trump has "confidence" in Comey, writing off Trump's tweets. Roger Stone gives a mysterious interview claiming communications with Trump and suggesting those communications were monitored.

Yates is scheduled to testify on her warnings about Flynn. Before the hearing, Trump points out on twitter that Obama also hired Flynn, and implies Yates is a leaker.

Trump downplays Yate's testimony, which reveals Yates believed Flynn was compromised and her warnings to the White House were urgent. Yates says that "if nothing was done" after the warnings it would be "concerning."

Clapper confirms that foreign allies passed the U.S. intelligence describing "suspicious contacts" between Trump advisors and Russian intelligence agents. Trump asserts that Clapper testified there is "no evidence" of collusion between Russia and Trump.

Yates testimony also reveals that Flynn was interviewed on White House grounds without a lawyer, that the White House knew Flynn had been interviewed by the FBI, that the White House asked DOJ about potential criminal proceedings and that the White House failed to notify the DOJ and other officials of Trump's travel ban, and strongly implies that the calls with the Russian ambassador were problematic and that Trump himself hid these from Pence, among other things (as previously mentioned).

The day of Yate's and Clapper's hearing, Rosenstein learns that Comey is to be fired. The next day, Rosenstein publishes a memo recommending Comey be fired for reasons that tend to criticize Comey for being too hard on Clinton. Trump had criticized Comey for going too easy on Clinton 6 days earlier. Trump cites the memo as the reason he fired Comey, saying he believes Rosenstein wrote it because of Comey's "poor performance before Congress." When asked later if he asked Rosenstein for a recommendation to fire Comey, Trump doesn't answer but says he was going to fire Comey anyway.

In Comey's termination letter, Trump stresses that Comey informed him "on three separate occasions" that he is not under investigation. Trump's lawyers assert there are no connections to Russia in the last 10 years of Trump's tax returns, except for some exceptions.

In an apparent attempt to intimidate him, Trump warns Comey that he "better hope that there are no 'tapes' of our conversations before he starts leaking to the press." Trump continues to rant about leakers, accusing Comey of being a leaker and charging that he had long ago asked Comey to "find the LEAKERS in the intelligence community."

The day after firing Comey, Trump meets with Russian ambassadors Kislyak and Lavrov in the Oval Office. Apparently, Trump hoped to make deals for closer cooperation and warmer relations between the United States and Russia and, reportedly, Trump told Lavrov firing Comey had relieved "great pressure." Trump described the meeting as "very, very good."

However, following the meeting, Trump is besieged by a series of dramatic leaks, alleging his incompetence and deep, sordid ties to Russia. Trump wonders "when does it end?" 

Trump posits that Comey will leak more than anybody could possibly imagine, in such a way as to be potentially "totally illegal" but definitely "very cowardly."


Trump told Comey he wanted his "loyalty," expressed his hopes that Comey could "see his way to letting Flynn go," asked Comey to "lift the cloud" of the Russia investigation over his dealmaking before firing him. For the question of "what was Trump's intent?" behind these actions, Comey and Trump give very different interpretations.



